  "text": "Sign in to your XDA account Summary Online recreation of Windows XP in a browser offers a nostalgic experience, complete with pre-installed games. Project is a faithful remake of Windows XP, including file system, programs, and XP-style dialogs. Recreated Windows XP isn't the actual OS but a nostalgic trip down memory lane; the creator will hopefully add more features. When was the last time you used Windows XP? For some of us, it's likely the last time we booted it in a virtual machine, while others may not have touched it ever since they upgraded to Vista. Either way, hearing that nostalgic login jingle is enough to send me back a few decades. If you want a short, sharp dose of nostalgia without busting open your virtual machines, then why not give this online recreation of Windows XP a try? All you need to do is boot it up in your browser, and you'll be transported back to the early 2000s. Plus, there are a ton of games on it. Yeah, pre-installed games that come with the operating system. That's something you don't see on Windows 11 anymore. Related This faithful remake of Windows XP is a fun way to relive the past In a post on the Windows subreddit, user ducbao414 showed off one of their projects. It's a pretty faithful recreation of Windows XP that you can run within your browser, complete with capturing your keyboard so you can type stuff in. Here's how they describe the project: Experience Windows XP in the browser Deploy it on your own server: GitHub repo I made this Windows XP-in-the-browser project a while ago as a way to revisit the nostalgia of my childhood, and hopefully bring back some memories for others too. Today, July 13, marks 25 years since Windows XP development first began, so it felt like a fitting time to share it. So, how was it done? Before you get the wrong idea, it's not actually Windows XP being deployed within your browser. Instead, it's a recreation that the creator designed to relive their nostalgic memories, and they've decided to show it off for everyone who wants to check it out. As such, you're pretty limited in what you can do; for instance, the Internet Explorer icon isn't actually IE, and it won't open webpages. However, given how good the recreation is, it's still an amazing and easy way to take a trip back down memory lane one more time. Here's hoping the creator continues adding things to this project to make it even better than it already is. If you want to go back to the real deal, check out how, two and a half decades later, enthusiasts are still keeping Windows XP alive and well on modern hardware. And if you want even more excuses to think back on Microsoft's golden era, be sure to read these Windows XP features we miss dearly on Windows 11. Windows",
